    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1870-04-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1870-04-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="249" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d249">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 250.</note>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Thornton</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr. Fish</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington,</hi>
                        </placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1870-04-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">April</hi> 2, 1870.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> In reply to your note of yesterday’s date,
                            I have the honor to inform you that although I am aware of the
                            announcement recently made by the Canadian government of their intention
                            to issue no more licenses to foreign fishermen, I have received no
                            official information to that effect from the Governor General of
                            Canada.</p>
                <p>Nor am I aware of the existence of any recent law or regulations which
                            may have been issued upon the subject of the fisheries. I will, however,
                            without delay, make inquiries upon the subject from the Governor
                            General, and will have the honor of communicating to you the result.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>EDWARD THORNTON.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
